         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25/4/64. ¶ My dear Bentham. ¶  ¶ Your kind letter of 25/2/64 calls for an acknowledgement. ¶   ¶ I am glad that you so rapidly push on the investigation of the Leguminosae, and feel sure we shall be i...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">64.04.25a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, ff. 144-5.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">25/4/64.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Bentham.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your kind letter of 25/2/64 calls for an acknowledgement.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">In this edition as 64-02-25a.</p>
               </note>
               <seg style=""> </seg>I am glad that you so rapidly push on the investigation of the <name key="Leguminosae">Leguminosae</name>, and feel sure we shall be indebted to you for a magnific essay of these plants, since no Botanist ever has so comprehensively &amp; so extensively examined them like you. It will afford me also the opportunity of resuming early my labor on the flora of Victoria. I wished you would throw out of vol II<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham (1863-78), volume 2.</p>
               </note> the small orders &amp; insert all the <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name>. This would give me my own set soon back again, so that I may at last finish vol II of flor. Vict. You will find the <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name> so extensively preexamined, that it will be comparatively an easy task to master them for your work. Just these two orders would form a fair extent of material<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">The line is marked with a cross in the margin against</seg> extent of.</p>
               </note> for vol. II &amp; then the other small orders with <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name> would occupy the 3. vol and bring the orders forward as far as <name key="Epacrideae">Epacrideae</name>, which ought to be included in <name key="Monopetalae">Monopetalae</name> or rather <name key="Corolliflorae">Corolliflorae</name>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Will you kindly let me know whether you want <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name> for vol. III. and also any supplem. to vol. I. I have some notes further for the purpose, but it would be a waste of time copying them should they not be wanted.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When will Dr Hookers Manual on N Z pl. be completed?<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Hooker (1864-7).</p>
               </note> I have recently placed my rather extensive collection of N Z plants in order &amp; have a good many not mentioned in the Flora,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Hooker (1853-5).</p>
               </note> e.g. <name key="Dicksonia%20dubia">Dicksonia dubia</name>, <name key="Cystopteris%20fragilis">Cystopteris fragilis</name>, Asplen<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Asplenium">Asplenium</name>.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> Trichoman[e]s, several <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name> &amp;c. Will you kindly direct Dr Hookers attention also to the fact, that several NZ mosses are published in the Linnaea of 1853 from my collections.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">C. Müller &amp; Hampe (1853).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have as yet no word about several boxes (successively numbered) &amp; sent to you &amp; feel considerable uneasiness on the subject. Could not one of your assistants keep a regular record of the arrivals? If a consignment is missing it <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">may</hi>
               </seg> be traced out soon afterwards, but <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">never</hi>
               </seg> after a time in London. Of this I have some sad evidence in some of my collections sent via London to the continent, or rather to London for being despatched to the continent.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M had been concerned for some time about the possible loss of consignments during transshipment in London. See for example, M to C. Rafn, 24 May 1963 (feared loss of Inca gold ornaments) and M to J. Lange, 8 June 1863 (in this edition as 63-06-08a), where he discusses general arrangements to minimize losses. </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I differ from you in regard to the limitation of <name key="Eugenia">Eugenia</name>. In my opinion it is not sufficient reason to disperse the species of a large &amp; natural genus into a number of artificial ones, because the number of the species is so copious.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to G. Bentham, 12 December 1863, and G. Bentham to M, 25 February 1864 (in this edition as 64-02-25a).</p>
               </note> If this was a sufficient reason, such genera as <name key="Solanum">Solanum</name>, <name key="Senecio">Senecio</name>, <name key="Panicum">Panicum</name>, <name key="Erica">Erica</name> &amp;c ought unavoidably be disrupted, not to the benefit of our science. All the distinctions apparent (&amp; of course fluctuant) in <name key="Acmene">Acmene</name>,<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Acmena</seg>?</p>
               </note>
               <name key="Jambosa">Jambosa</name>, <name key="Syzigium">Syzigium</name> are of sectional but not of generic value. Moreover I disapprove of the generic &amp; specific limitations of the <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name>, as expound by Berg in Mart flor Brasiliana,<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">O. Berg (1857-9).</p>
               </note> and have told so Martius.<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">No letter to Martius commenting on Berg's treatment has been found. </p>
               </note> I have a number of these plants here in my Museum out of the Petersburg collection &amp; feel confident they are not safely defined. [Indeed] the <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name> of the fl. Brasiliana bear not a favorable comparison with the <name key="Leguminosae">Leguminosae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham (1859-76); part 1, pp 1 - 350 had been published by January 1862, see TL2.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Could you kindly arrange that I receive a copy of Dr Hookers manual as soon as out?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In putting my huge collection of <name key="Epacrideae">Epacrideae</name> into final order I perceive by new forms the very trifling differences of some of the genera [st]ill further impaired. It is much to be regretted that RBr. did not as he was half inclined to do keep up that fine large &amp; natural genus <name key="Styphelia">Styphelia</name>, as I shall probably do in the plants of Victoria.<note xml:id="ftn14" type="footnote" n="14">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M retained the concept of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Styphelia">Styphelia</name>
                     </seg>, continuing to describe species under that generic name until 1893, when he introduced <seg style="font-style: italic; ">S. kingiana</seg> in B93.09.05, p. 78; Bentham (1863-78), vol. 4, split the group into more taxa. See also J. Willis (1972), p. 496, and Lucas (2003), pp. 269-72.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The enclosed carte de visite is for Prof. Harvey.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">With cordiality</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In the Bot Zeitung for 1851 Regel described a South Austr <name key="Pultenaea">Pultenaea</name> as an <name key="Aotus%20W%C3%BCrthii">Aotus Würthii</name>. I am not certain which.<note xml:id="ftn15" type="footnote" n="15">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Regel (1851), col. 596.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Portulaca%20oleracea">Portulaca oleracea</name> has since the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">last</hi>
               </seg> year become as frequent in the streets of Melbourne as I saw it in the city of Rio de Janeiro<note xml:id="ftn16" type="footnote" n="16">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The species is not mentioned in M's notebook of plants seen in the vicinity of Rio de Janeiro; see Breviary of plants observed near Rio Janeiro, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne, RB MS M43.</p>
                  <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
               </note>
            </p>
